    <section class="ae-container-fluid ae-container-fluid--full">
      <header class="rk-portfolio-cover  item-inside-1 overlay">
        <div class="item-inside__meta">
          <h1 class="ae-u-bolder rk-portfolio-title ">Berkeley Student Information Systems</h1>
          <p class="ae-theta rk-portfolio-category ">User Interface / User Experience</p>
        </div>
      </header>
  
      <div class="ae-container-fluid ae-container-fluid--inner rk-portfolio--inner">
        <div class="ae-grid ae-grid--collapse au-xs-ptp-1">
          <div class="ae-grid__item item-lg-8 au-lg-ptp-1">
            <h6>The Problem</h6>
            <p><h2>Students cannot understand the relationship between their bill and their financial aid.</h2></p>
            <p>The Student Information Systems (SIS) Project is Berkeleyâ€™s initiative to replace the aging and disparate student systems. The SIS Project needed help merging billing and financial aid into a single, smooth student experience.</p>

          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ae-grid ae-grid--collapse au-xs-ptp-1 au-xs-pbp-1">
          <div class="ae-grid__item item-lg-8 item-lg--offset-2">
            <h4 class="ae-u-bolder">My Role</h4>
            <p>As a UI/UX designer on a team of two other student designers, Cassidy Hsieh and Tim Guan, I provided a design proposal and prototype of a tool that helps students understand how their bill affects their financial aid. I particularly drove the creation of the mid-fidelity and high-fidelity mockups.</p>
            <!-- <p class="ae-eta">We conducted research by interviewing backers on Indiegogo and entrepreneurs who have run at least one successful campaign on the platform. We discovered that people's main concerns with profile pages fall into the categories: <b>reliability, accessability, activity,</b> and <b>personalization.</b></p> -->
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ae-grid ae-grid--collapse">
          <div class="ae-grid__item item-lg-5">
            <h4>User Research</h4>
            <p>We began by studying the financial web applications of several other universities and explored their layouts of students' financial information.</b></p>
          </div>
          <div class="ae-grid__item item-lg-6 item-lg--offset-1">
          	<img src="assets/img/financialsystems.png" alt="Other university financial systems">
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ae-grid ae-grid--collapse" style="padding-top: 20px;">
          <div class="ae-grid__item item-lg-5">
            <h6>Surveys</h6>
            <p>We received 23 responses to an exploratory survey to better understand students' experiences with Cal financial aid and billing systems.</p>
            <img src="assets/img/sissurvey.png" alt="Survey Spreadsheet">
          </div>
          <div class="ae-grid__item item-lg-6 item-lg--offset-1">
            <h6>User Interviews</h6>
            <p>We also conducted several in-depth user interviews by having students walk us through the process of paying their bill and understanding MyFinAid (financial aid program). We then constructed user profiles to represent our student users.</p>
            <img src="assets/img/sis-interviews.png" alt="Student Persona">
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ae-grid ae-grid--collapse" style="padding-top: 30px;">
          <div class="ae-grid__item">
            <h4>Key Insights and Ideation</h4>
            <ol>
            	<b><li>Students feel they cannot trust the system because it lacks specific information about the allocation of financial resources</li></b>
            		<ul>
            			<li>Provide a breakdown of fees and where to go with questions</li>
            			<li>Display information icons next to each charged item so students know what each charge covers</li>
            			<li>Stay consistent with color coding across the platform</li>
            		</ul>
            	<b><li>Students are not directly presented with the most important information</li></b>
            		<ul>
            			<li>Add a checklist with tasks that students must complete</li>
            			<li>Display visuals on how student loads and financial aid affect billing</li>
            			<li>Provide disclaimers before potentially risky actions (ex: taking out loans)</li>
            		</ul>
            	<b><li>Students sometimes find the terminology confusing or misleading</li></b>
            		<ul>
            			<li>Display information icons beside each item with definitions and instructions</li>
            			<li>Create a page for "Understanding your bill" containing an index of terms</li>
            		</ul>
            	<b><li>Students are frustrated with the systems lack of response</li></b>
            		<ul>
            			<li>Display a banner that clearly states a payment is being processed after one has been paid</li>
            			<li>Place visual cues to indicate when actions have been finalized (such as graying out an option)</li>
            			<li>Create an online discussion where students for students to ask and answer questions</li>
            		</ul>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ae-grid ae-grid--collapse" style="padding-top: 30px;">
          <div class="ae-grid__item">
            <h4>Prototyping</h4>
            <p>We used small multiples to help us design different layouts and weigh the pros and cons of each layout. We used a combination of user testing and our own discretion to narrow our selection of possible layouts.</p>
             <img src="assets/img/smallmultiples.png" alt="Small Multiples of MyFinances">
         </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ae-grid ae-grid--collapse" style="padding-top: 30px;">
          <div class="ae-grid__item">
            <h4>Final Deliverables</h4>
            <p>Some notable design features include:</p>
            <ul>
            	<li>Having amount due, the most important piece of information, displayed at the top</li>
            	<li>Representing the relationship between financial aid and the monthly bill with a progress bar. Different segments on the bar show how much of the bill has been covered by existing aid, scholarships, or loans, and how much is left to be paid.</li>
            	<li>Maintaining the colors of each category to the descriptions in the form of a bar on the side</li>
            	<li>Having a more descriptive notifications section</li>
            	<li>Offering a detailed description of the bill should students have any questions</li>
            	<li>Placing the "Frequently Asked Questions" in the footer rather than allowing it to take up its own column</li>
            </ul>
            <img class="padding" src="assets/img/sis1.png" alt="Home Page High-Fidelity Mockup">
            <p class="caption">MyFinances "Home" page</p>
            <img class="padding" src="assets/img/sis2.png" alt="Bill Details Page Indiegogo High-Fidelity">
            <p class="caption">MyFinances "Bill details" page</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
